>-p-</i> being English. Both forms are common in Ireland. The surname <i>Thompson</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen   and of its Swedish cognate <b>Thomsson</b>. Compare   Thomson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomson","meanings":["Scottish, English and northern Irish: variant of   Thompson  .","Scottish: sometimes an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>McThomas</i>; see   McTavish  ,   McComish  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen  . Compare   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thom","meanings":["Scottish and English: from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . In Scotland, <i>Thom</i> is also an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Thom</i>, see   McComb  .","German: from the personal name <i>Thom</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . This surname is also found in France.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 譚, see   Tan   1."]},{"name":"Tomson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thompsom","meanings":["Altered form of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Tompson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Thompson III was born about 1250, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Thomas Thompson II, was 24 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Thompson II, was 16. He married Mrs Thomas Thompson III about 1280, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. H